  "doc_id": "35821",
  "text": "To compensate for imperfect radiofrequency excitation at 7T caused by B 1 þ variations along the SC [CITATION_1] and avoid subsequent T 1 estimation bias [CITATION_2] , an offline B 1 þ -inhomogeneity correction implemented in MATLAB (The Mathworks, Natick, MA, USA) and described in [CITATION_3] , was first performed using the acquired B 1 þ maps. T 1 maps were subsequently denoised using a block-matching and filtering algorithm (BM4D) [CITATION_4] to compensate for inherent noise propagation within the MP2RAGE uniform image ratio (see Appendix 2 of [CITATION_5] . For further processing, 3D T 1 volumes were resliced at each vertebral level (C1-to-C7), using the c3D reslice-identity function (ITK-SNAP, UPENN, PA, USA) and the GRE images as reference, leading to a total of 7 slices per subject. When 2 vol were acquired (in case of pronounced SC curvature), reslicing was performed using the most adequate slab (usually 1st slab for C1 to C4 and 2nd slab for C5 to C7, see Fig. 2 ).",
